#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1174
msgid "Loading a Scene as a Sub-Xsheet"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1175
msgid ""
"Previously saved OpenToonz scenes can be loaded in a Xsheet/Timeline as "
"Sub-Xsheets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1177
msgid ""
"Every time a scene is loaded as a Sub-Xsheet, its contents are imported "
"into the current project database according to the project default "
"folders, in the same way as it would be if every single level was "
"imported (see  :ref:`Using the File Browser <using_the_file_browser>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1179
msgid ""
"This allows you to create a library of basic animations that can be "
"loaded and edited in other Xsheets/Timelines to create more complex "
"animations without affecting the original files or drawings. Even when "
"the same Sub-Xsheet is loaded twice, it is handled as if two different "
"Sub-Xsheets were loaded, whose contents and levels can be edited "
"separately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1181
msgid ""
"To keep the database well-ordered you can also activate the **Create Sub-"
"folder when Importing Sub-Xsheet** option in the Preferences > Loading "
"dialog, that will automatically create, in the project default folder, a "
"folder named as the Sub-Xsheet you are importing where the levels from "
"the Sub-Xsheet will be copied."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1183
msgid ""
"Once a Sub-Xsheet is loaded, its levels are available in the Scene Cast "
"in a sub-folder named as the scene you loaded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1185
msgid ""
"If the camera settings of the scene you are loading as a Sub-Xsheet are "
"different from those of your current scene, you will be prompted whether "
"to keep the Sub-Xsheet original camera settings, or to apply the camera "
"settings of the current scene to the Sub-Xsheet as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1187
msgid ""
"If the scene you import contains a file whose name is the same of a file "
"already existing in the destination default folder, you will prompted "
"whether to keep the existing file, overwrite it with the new one, or "
"rename it adding a suffix you can decide. In this way you can control if "
"files you are importing were already imported previously, or manage files"
" that share the same name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1189
msgid "**To load a previously saved scene as a Sub-Xsheet:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1193
msgid "Choose File > **Load Level** and use the browser to load a TNZ file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1195
msgid ""
"Choose File > **Load As Sub-Xsheet** and use the browser to load a TNZ "
"file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1197
msgid ""
"Use the OpenToonz standard browser to drag the scene icon to the Scene "
"Cast pane, the Xsheet/Timeline or the viewer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1199
msgid ""
"In the file browser right-click the scene icon and select **Load As Sub-"
"Xsheet** in the menu that opens."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1201
msgid ""
"OpenToonz scene files can also be loaded by dragging and dropping them "
"from the Windows Explorer or macOS Finder to the Scene Cast, "
"Xsheet/Timeline, or the viewer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1207
msgid "Exploding Sub-Xsheets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1208
msgid ""
"Sub-Xsheets can be exploded to automatically bring their content into the"
" Xsheet/Timeline where they are exposed. When exploding a Sub-Xsheet it's"
" possible to choose to bring to the main Xsheet/Timeline, when needed, "
"the pegbars to which columns are linked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1210
msgid ""
"When a Sub-Xsheet is exploded, its columns/layers and the related FX "
"nodes are displayed as a group in the FX Schematic, in order to better "
"retrieve them (see  :ref:`Using the FX Schematic "
"<using_the_fx_schematic>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1212
msgid ""
"If FXs are applied to the Sub-Xsheet column/layer, they will not be "
"applied to the exploded columns, but the disconnected FX nodes will "
"remain as reference in the FX Schematic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1214
msgid "**To explode a Sub-Xsheet:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1216
msgid ""
"Select the Sub-Xsheet column/layer in the Xsheet/Timeline or in the "
"Schematic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1220
msgid "Choose Xsheet > **Explode**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1222
msgid ""
"Right-click the Sub-Xsheet column header and choose **Explode** from the "
"menu that opens."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1224
msgid ""
"Choose whether to bring relevant pegbars to the main Xsheet/Timeline, or "
"to bring columns/layers only, then click the OK button."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1230
msgid "Saving a Sub-Xsheet as a Scene"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1231
msgid ""
"The content of a Sub-Xsheet can be saved as a standard scene, i.e. a TNZ "
"file, in order to be loaded as a stand-alone scene or to be available for"
" reuse in other scenes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1233
msgid ""
"The Sub-Xsheet content will be saved according to the current project "
"settings for default folders, as if you were saving a scene file (see  "
":ref:`Project Default Folders <project_default_folders>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1235
msgid "**To save a Sub-Xsheet as a scene:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1237
msgid ""
"Open the Sub-Xsheet you want to save, so that its contents are displayed "
"in the Xsheet/Timeline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1239
msgid ""
"Choose Xsheet > **Save Sub-Xsheet As...** and use the browser to save the"
" scene file (see  :ref:`Saving and Loading Scenes "
"<saving_and_loading_scenes>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1245
msgid "Creating a Soundtrack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1246
msgid ""
"Audio clips can be loaded and edited in order to create a soundtrack for "
"the scene; natively supported file formats are non-compressed ``WAV`` and"
" ``AIFF``  files at 8 and 16 bit. If FFmpeg is installed and configured "
"in Preferences > Import/Export dialog, ``MP3`` audio files can be loaded "
"too. There is no limit to the number of audio clips that can be loaded in"
" a scene."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1248
msgid ""
"To load an audio clip you can use the Browser room; if an audio clip is "
"imported, it is saved in the *+extras* folder (see  :ref:`Using the File "
"Browser <using_the_file_browser>`  ). Loaded audio clips are also stored "
"in the Audio folder of the Scene Cast."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1250
msgid ""
"Each loaded audio clip is exposed in a different Xsheet column or "
"Timeline layer as a series of visible sound waves to make the editing job"
" easier; the number of frames it spans depends on the length of the audio"
" file and the frame rate set for the current scene. For example an audio "
"clip 3 seconds long, imported into a scene whose frame rate is 12, will "
"occupy 36 frames; if imported in a scene whose frame rate is 24 will "
"occupy 72 frames (see  :ref:`Setting the Frame Rate "
"<setting_the_frame_rate>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1252
msgid "|audio|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1254
msgid ""
"Audio columns/layers can be edited the way you edit any other "
"column/layer. Its header contains the following information about the "
"content:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1256
msgid ""
"**Name**, by default is the number of the column/layer the audio is "
"exposed in. e.g. Col5."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1258
msgid ""
"**Render toggle** (|preview|) allowing you to include or not the audio "
"column/layer content in the rendering."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1260
msgid ""
"**Camera stand toggle** (|camera_stand|) allowing you to include or not "
"the column/layer content when scrubbing the audio with the current frame "
"cursor (see below)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1264
msgid ""
"**Additional settings** button (|additional_settings|) allowing you to "
"set the volume."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1266
msgid "**Loudspeaker** icon that lets you play the contents back."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1268
msgid ""
"The **Level Settings** dialog is available for audio clips as well, "
"allowing you to check the location of the related file, or to update the "
"loading path to a different location, or to a different file (see  "
":ref:`Editing Level Settings <editing_level_settings>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1270
msgid ""
"The soundtrack you define with audio clips will be created by merging all"
" of the contents of audio columns/layers according to the volume you set "
"for each of them. While it cannot be played back when using the playback "
"controls in the viewer, it can be scrubbed with the current frame cursor "
"in the Xsheet frame column, the Timeline frame ruler or in the viewer "
"framebar, and played back when a scene is previewed (see  :ref:`Editing "
"Audio Clips <editing_audio_clips>`  and  :ref:`Previewing the Animation "
"<previewing_the_animation>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1272
msgid ""
"When a scene is rendered in a file format supporting audio, (MP4, MOV, "
"WebM or AVI), the soundtrack will be included in the file (see  "
":ref:`Rendering the Animation <rendering_the_animation>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1274
msgid ""
"Audio clips loaded in Sub-Xsheets will not be included in the output "
"soundtrack (see  :ref:`Using Sub-Xsheets <using_sub-xsheets>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1276
msgid ""
"As the soundtrack cannot be played back when viewing files in the "
"OpenToonz flipbook, you can activate the **Use Default Viewer for Movie "
"Formats** option in the Preferences > General dialog, in order to view "
"files with their own default viewer, e.g. QuickTime for the MOV format, "
"thus playing back the soundtrack as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1278
msgid "**To play the contents of an audio column/layer back:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1280
msgid ""
"Click the loudspeaker icon available in the header of the column/layer. "
"Click it again to stop the playback."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1282
msgid "**To set the volume of an audio column/layer:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1284
msgid ""
"Click the Additional settings button (|additional_settings|) and use the "
"Volume slider in there."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1286
msgid ""
"**To include or exclude an audio when scrubbing the audio with the "
"current frame cursor**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1288
msgid ""
"Click the Camera stand toggle (|camera_stand|) on the column/layer "
"header. If you right-click the toggle you can select commands from a menu"
" that opens that let you affect several columns/layers at the same time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1290
msgid ""
"**To include or exclude the audio column/layer contents from the "
"rendering:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1292
msgid ""
"Click the Render toggle (|preview|) on the column/layer header. If you "
"right-click the toggle you can select commands from a menu that opens "
"that let you affect several columns/layers at the same time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1296
msgid ""
"Click the Lock toggle (|lock|) on the column/layer header. If you right-"
"click the toggle you can select commands from a menu that opens that let "
"you lock or unlock several columns/layers at the same time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1302
msgid "Editing Audio Clips"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1303
msgid ""
"Once loaded, audio clips can be moved up and down in a Xsheet column, "
"left and right in a Timeline layer, or to a different column/layer, in "
"order to be played starting from a certain frame of the animation. They "
"can be trimmed to select a part of the whole clip and edited, by deleting"
" or copying some sections, using standard edit commands the same way you "
"use them on standard levels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1305
msgid ""
"When a clip is trimmed, the trimmed part is not eliminated, but hidden, "
"and it has a colored horizontal marker at its starting or ending, "
"according to where it was trimmed: it is possible to retrieve the trimmed"
" part by moving back the markers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1307
msgid ""
"When a clip is split into sections by deleting, cutting or moving "
"operations, it is automatically duplicated and trimmed to create the "
"right result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1309
msgid ""
"Audio clips can be moved and pasted only to empty columns/layers, or to "
"other audio columns/layers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1311
msgid ""
"All the editing does not affect the file on disk, as it refers only to "
"the way the clip is used in the scene."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1313
msgid ""
"To find a particular section in an audio file, you can examine it by "
"scrubbing it with the current frame cursor, either in the Xsheet frame "
"column, the Timeline frame ruler, in the viewer framebar, or by selecting"
" any section and automatically playing it back together with the "
"animation. This allows you to easily spot and excerpt the sections you "
"need from an audio file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1315
msgid "**To select audio clips:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1319
msgid "Click and drag to select a section of the clip."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1321
msgid "Shift-click a clip cell to extend the selection up to that cell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1323
msgid ""
"In the Xsheet, click the vertical strip available on the left of the "
"clip, to select the whole clip."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1325
msgid ""
"In the Timeline, click the horizontal strip available on the top of the "
"clip, to select the whole clip."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1327
msgid "**To edit audio clips with the Edit menu commands:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1333
msgid ""
"Use the **Cut** command to eliminate the selection from the "
"Xsheet/Timeline and keep it in memory for further operations. The cell "
"elimination causes the following cells to shift up in the Xsheet or left "
"in the Timeline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1335
msgid ""
"Use the **Paste** command to paste the selection kept in memory in the "
"Xsheet/Timeline, starting from the selected insertion cell. The command "
"causes the following cells to shift down in the Xsheet or right in the "
"Timeline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1343
msgid "**To move a clip selection in the Xsheet:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1347
msgid ""
"**Click** the vertical strip available on the left of the clip cells, and"
" drag them to move them to a new position."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1349
msgid ""
"**Ctrl-click** (PC) or **Cmd-click** (Mac) the vertical strip available "
"on the left of the clip cells, and drag them to the new position "
"duplicating them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1351
msgid ""
"**Shift-click** the vertical strip available on the left of the clip "
"cells, and drag them to the new position inserting them if other audio "
"clips are loaded in the destination cells."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1353
msgid ""
"**Alt-click** the vertical strip available on the left of the clip cells,"
" and drag them to the new position overwriting any other audio clips "
"previously loaded in the destination cells."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1355
msgid "**To move a clip selection in the Timeline:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1359
msgid ""
"**Click** the horizontal strip available on the top of the clip cells, "
"and drag them to move them to a new position."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1361
msgid ""
"**Ctrl-click** (PC) or **Cmd-click** (Mac) the horizontal strip available"
" on the top of the clip cells, and drag them to the new position "
"duplicating them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1363
msgid ""
"**Shift-click** the horizontal strip available on the top of the clip "
"cells, and drag them to the new position inserting them if other audio "
"clips are loaded in the destination cells."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1365
msgid ""
"**Alt-click** the horizontal strip available on the top of the clip "
"cells, and drag them to the new position overwriting any other audio "
"clips previously loaded in the destination cells."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1367
msgid ""
"When it is not possible to release the selection, a red outline is "
"displayed instead of the selection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1369
msgid "**To trim an audio clip:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1373
msgid "Click and drag the starting of a clip to trim its starting part."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1375
msgid "Click and drag the ending of a clip to trim its ending part."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1377
msgid "Click and drag the marker of a trimmed clip to redefine the trimmed part."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1379
#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1408
msgid "**To scrub audio clips:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1383
msgid ""
"Drag the Xsheet frame cursor up or down to scrub all the audio columns "
"whose Camera Stand toggle is active."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1385
msgid ""
"Drag the Timeline frame cursor left or right to scrub all the audio "
"layers whose Camera Stand toggle is active."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1387
msgid ""
"Drag the frame cursor in the viewer framebar to scrub all the audio "
"columns whose Camera Stand toggle is active."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1389
msgid ""
"Windows only: In the Xsheet, click and drag on the dashed vertical strip "
"available on the right of the audio column cells, the selected section "
"will be automatically played back."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1391
msgid ""
"Windows only: In the Timeline, click and drag on the dashed horizontal "
"strip available on the bottom of the audio layer cells, the selected "
"section will be automatically played back."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1397
msgid "Lip Synching"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1398
msgid ""
"When you need to synchronize the movement of a character’s lips with the "
"sound of the speech, you can take advantage of the possibility to examine"
" the audio files loaded in the scene."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1400
msgid ""
"Once you have created different mouth images, you can analyze the audio "
"files to find where to place specific mouth drawings. If mouth drawings "
"belong to one single animation level, you can quickly change the mouth "
"drawing at a specific frame by picking drawings from the level strip or "
"by flipping through drawings using one of the **Skeleton** tool "
"(|skeleton|) features (see :ref:`Using the Level Strip "
"<using_the_level_strip>`  and :ref:`Animating Models <animating_models>`"
"  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1402
msgid ""
"The breakdown of audio files can be done by looking at the sound wave in "
"the scene column, for example to spot where each word starts; by "
"scrubbing the loaded audio clips with the current frame cursor either in "
"the Xsheet/Timeline frame ruler or in the Viewer framebar; and by "
"listening to specific sections of the audio files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1404
msgid ""
"When mouth images are placed in the proper place, you can check the sync "
"by scrubbing or selecting again the audio file section you are interested"
" in, because while listening to the selected audio section, the viewer "
"will display the related animation frames."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1406
msgid ""
"This technique can be used in any case you need the sound to be perfectly"
" synchronized with the action, for example a character playing an "
"instrument, or a scene based on the rhythm of a music."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1412
msgid ""
"Drag the Xsheet/Timeline frame cursor forward or backwards to scrub all "
"the audio levels whose Camera Stand toggle is active."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1414
msgid ""
"Drag the frame cursor in the Viewer framebar to scrub all the audio "
"columns whose Camera Stand toggle is active."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1416
msgid ""
"Windows only: click and drag on the dashed strip available on the audio "
"level cells: the selected section will be automatically played back."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1418
msgid "**To flip through the mouth drawings:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1422
msgid ""
"Select in the Xsheet or Timeline the animation level containing the mouth"
" drawings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1424
msgid ""
"Right-click in the viewer over the mouth drawing you want to flip "
"through, and choose the **Select** command related to the column/layer "
"containing the drawing you clicked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1426
msgid ""
"Choose the **Skeleton** tool (|skeleton|) and set the tool mode to "
"**Animate**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/working_in_xsheet.rst:1428
msgid ""
"In the viewer click the label with the level name on the right of the "
"current section pivot point and flip through following and previous "
"frames by doing one of the following:"
